Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Renewable energy sources play an increasingly important role in the global energy mix, as the effort to reduce the environmental impact of energy production increases.

Out of all the renewable energy alternatives, wind energy is one of the most developed technologies worldwide. The U.S Department of Energy has put together a guide to achieving operational efficiency using predictive maintenance practices.

Predictive maintenance uses sensor information and analysis methods to measure and predict degradation and future component capability. The idea behind predictive maintenance is that failure patterns are predictable and if component failure can be predicted accurately and the component is replaced before it fails, the costs of operation and maintenance will be much lower.

The sensors fitted across different machines involved in the process of energy generation collect data related to various environmental factors (temperature, humidity, wind speed, etc.) and additional features related to various parts of the wind turbine (gearbox, tower, blades, break, etc.).

Objective¶

“ReneWind” is a company working on improving the machinery/processes involved in the production of wind energy using machine learning and has collected data of generator failure of wind turbines using sensors. They have shared a ciphered version of the data, as the data collected through sensors is confidential (the type of data collected varies with companies). Data has 40 predictors, 20000 observations in the training set and 5000 in the test set.

The objective is to build various classification models, tune them, and find the best one that will help identify failures so that the generators could be repaired before failing/breaking to reduce the overall maintenance cost. The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

  • True positives (TP) are failures correctly predicted by the model. These will result in repairing costs.
  • False negatives (FN) are real failures where there is no detection by the model. These will result in replacement costs.
  • False positives (FP) are detections where there is no failure. These will result in inspection costs.

It is given that the cost of repairing a generator is much less than the cost of replacing it, and the cost of inspection is less than the cost of repair.

“1” in the target variables should be considered as “failure” and “0” represents “No failure”.

Data Description¶

  • The data provided is a transformed version of original data which was collected using sensors.
  • Train.csv - To be used for training and tuning of models.
  • Test.csv - To be used only for testing the performance of the final best model.
  • Both the datasets consist of 40 predictor variables and 1 target variable

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Model Building¶

Model evaluation criterion¶

The nature of predictions made by the classification model will translate as follows:

  • True positives (TP) are failures correctly predicted by the model.
  • False negatives (FN) are real failures in a generator where there is no detection by model.

  • False positives (FP) are failure detections in a generator where there is no failure.

  • The best metric will ensure that the maximum number of generator failures are predicted correctly by the model.

  • We focus on Recall, as greater the Recall, the higher the chances of minimizing false negatives.
  • We minimize false negatives because if a model predicts that a machine will have no failure when there will be a failure, it will increase the maintenance cost.

Function to output different metrics (including recall) on the train and test set and confusion matrix¶

In [31]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Defining scorer to be used for cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning¶

  • We want to reduce false negatives and will try to maximize "Recall".
  • To maximize Recall, we can use Recall as a scorer in cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning.

Business Insights and Conclusions¶

Best model and its performance¶

BaggingClassifier with undersampled data achieved a recall score of 0.896 on the test dataset, indicating that it correctly identified approximately 89.6% of the relevant instances of the target class. This means that the model effectively minimized the number of false negatives, which are instances of the positive class incorrectly classified as negative. However, while the recall score is relatively high, it's important to consider other performance metrics as well:

Precision: Precision measures the proportion of true positive predictions among all positive predictions made by the model. A high precision indicates that the model makes fewer false positive predictions. For BaggingClassifier with undersampled data, precision could be lower if the model tends to classify too many instances as positive, leading to false positives.

Accuracy: Accuracy measures the overall correctness of the model's predictions. While a high recall score indicates that the model is effective at capturing relevant instances, accuracy considers the overall performance across all classes. BaggingClassifier with undersampled data might achieve a high recall score, but its overall accuracy could be impacted if it misclassifies instances from other classes.

F1 Score: The F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall and provides a balanced assessment of the model's performance. It's important to consider F1 score along with recall to understand the trade-off between precision and recall. BaggingClassifier with undersampled data may have a high recall score, but if its precision is low, it might result in a lower F1 score.

Additionally, the choice of undersampling could affect the model's performance. Undersampling aims to balance class distribution by reducing the number of majority class instances, potentially leading to information loss and decreased performance.

In summary, BaggingClassifier with undersampled data achieved a high recall score on the test dataset, indicating its effectiveness in identifying positive instances.

Conclusions¶

Gradient Boosting:Training Recall score is 0.992 and Testing Recall: 0.856 Conclusion: The model performs well on the training data but shows a drop in recall on the testing data. It might be overfitting.

AdaBoost:Training Recall: 0.988. Testing Recall: 0.853 Conclusion: Similar to Gradient Boosting, AdaBoost also exhibits overfitting. The recall decreases on the testing data.

Random Forest: Training Recall: 0.933. Testing Recall: 0.885 Conclusion: The model generalizes reasonably well, but there’s still room for improvement.

XGBoost: Training Recall: 1.000. Testing Recall: 0.892. Conclusion: XGBoost achieves perfect recall on the training data but slightly lower recall on the testing data. It’s a strong contender.

Decision Tree:Training Recall: 0.917. Testing Recall: 0.885. Conclusion: Consistent recall, but overfitting might be a concern. Evaluate further.

Bagging: Training Recall (Oversampled): 1.000. Testing Recall (Oversampled): 0.874. Training Recall (Undersampled): 1.000. Testing Recall (Undersampled): 0.896. Training Recall (Original Sample): 0.972. Testing Recall (Original Sample): 0.741. Conclusion: Bagging with undersampled data performs well on both training and testing sets. It balances recall and other metrics.

Overall Conclusions: The best Models on Training and testing data are BaggingClassifier with undersampled data and XGBoost tuned with oversampled data. I decided to nominate the Bagging Classifier with undersampled data as it gave the highest recall score although compared to XGBoost the precision score is comparatively lower.

Best Model on Training Data: BaggingClassifier with oversampled data (perfect recall). Best Model on Testing Data: XGBoost tuned with oversampled data (high recall, good generalization)and BaggingClassifier with undersapled data.

Recommendations¶

-Renewind company should prioritize Models with High Recall: Given the cost structure where the cost of false negatives (failure without detection) is significantly higher than false positives (detection without failure), prioritize models with high recall scores on the test data. Models with high recall correctly identify a larger proportion of actual failures, minimizing the risk of undetected failures that would result in costly replacements.

-Renewind company should consider BaggingClassifier with Undersampled Data: The BaggingClassifier with undersampled data demonstrated a relatively high recall score on the test dataset (0.896). While other models like Gradient Boosting and AdaBoost performed well, BaggingClassifier with undersampled data could be considered due to its higher recall score, which is crucial for correctly identifying failures.

-The company should evaluate False Positive Rate: While recall is important, it's also essential to consider the false positive rate (the proportion of non-failures incorrectly classified as failures) due to the associated inspection costs. Models with lower false positive rates would lead to fewer unnecessary inspections, reducing inspection costs without significantly impacting the ability to detect failures.

-The company should validate results in real-world Scenarios: While model performance on the test dataset provides valuable insights, it's essential to validate the selected model's performance in real-world scenarios. The company should conduct pilot tests or implement the model in a controlled environment to assess its effectiveness in identifying failures and optimizing maintenance costs.

-The company should conduct continuous monitoring and improvement: Maintenance processes and data collection systems evolve over time. Continuously monitor model performance and incorporate new data to improve model accuracy and effectiveness. As such, the company should regularly reevaluate the selected model's performance and consider retraining or fine-tuning it as necessary to adapt to changing conditions and requirements.

-By prioritizing models with high recall, considering the false positive rate and validating results in real-world scenarios, ReneWind can select a model that effectively identifies failures in wind turbine generators, thereby optimizing maintenance costs and ensuring efficient operations.
